    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Sacred temples of worship of native Hawaiian people, typically rectangular in shape and situated on hill tops or mountain slopes. Heiaus have carved designs of deep symbolism. For similar structures from East Polynesia, use "maraes."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046811/Kaeppler, Oceanic Art (1997)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Templo o santuario exterior hawaiano de época pre-cristiana. Para estructuras similares del Este de la Polinesia, use "marae".</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Heiaus zijn heilige eretempels van autochtone Hawaïanen. Deze constructies hebben doorgaans een rechthoekige vorm en staan op heuveltoppen of berghellingen. Heiaus hebben uitgesneden patronen met een diepe symboliek. Gebruik 'maraes' voor vergelijkbare constructies in Oost-Polynesië.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>夏威夷原住民宗教信仰之聖廟。此類結構物通常呈長方形，坐落於丘頂或山坡上。廟中有象徵意味濃厚的雕刻設計。玻里尼西亞東部有類似結構物，稱為「瑪磊石廟（maraes）」。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Heiliger Tempel der Verehrung der hawaiianischen Eingeborenen, üblicherweise rechteckig und auf einer Hügelkuppe oder an einem Berghang gelegen. Ein Heiau besitzt Schnitzereien mit symbolischer Bedeutung. Für ein ähnliches Bauwerk aus Ost-Polynesien, siehe "Marae".</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Templos sagrados de adoração do povo nativo havaiano, geralmente de forma retangular e situados no topo de colinas ou declives de montanhas. Heiaus têm desenhos esculpidos de simbolismo profundo. Para estruturas semelhantes da Polinésia oriental, use "maraes".</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
